first-name><address><city>Cincinnati</city><state>OH</state><country>US</country></address></addressbook><residence><country>US</country></residence></us-applicant></us-applicants><inventors><inventor sequence="00" designation="us-only"><addressbook><last-name>Sauser</last-name><first-name>Frank</first-name><address><city>Cincinnati</city><state>OH</state><country>US</country></address></addressbook></inventor></inventors></us-parties></us-bibliographic-data-application><abstract id="abstract"><p id="p-0001" num="0000">A fluidizable bed (<b>10</b>) comprises a receptacle (<b>12</b>), a diffuser board (<b>14</b>) dividing the receptacle (<b>12</b>) into a plenum (<b>16</b>) and a fluidizable medium container (<b>20</b>), a fluidizable medium (<b>30</b>) residing in the container, and a partition (<b>32</b>) dividing the plenum (<b>16</b>) into a first chamber (<b>34</b>) adapted to receive a first stream (<b>36</b>) of fluidizing medium (<b>30</b>) and a second chamber (<b>40</b>) adapted to receive a second stream (<b>42</b>) of fluidizing medium (<b>30</b>). In operation a first stream (<b>36</b>) of the fluidizing medium (<b>30</b>) is admitted to the first chamber (<b>34</b>) and a second stream (<b>42</b>) of the fluidizing medium (<b>30</b>) is admitting to the second chamber (<b>40</b>). By admitting the fluidizing medium (<b>30</b>) to the chambers in a phased, cyclic fashion the benefits of lateral rotation are achieved in a fluidizable bed (<b>10</b>).</p></abstract></us-patent-application>